04094nam a22005535i 9780889209329DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20062004xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892093297 a10.51644/97808892093292doi  a(DE-B1597)667873  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPN149 .G85 2006 7aLAN0050002bisacsh04a808a808.02a808/.021 aGunnars, Kristjana, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aStranger at the Door :bWriters and the Act of Writing /cKristjana Gunnars. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (138 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgements -- tThe Art of Solitude -- tThe Diasporic Imagination -- tThe Home and the Artist -- tTranscultural Appropriation -- tTheory and Fiction -- tWriting and Silence -- tOn Writing Short Books -- tPoetry and the Idea of Home -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt the beginning of a new writing project—whether it’s the first page of a new novel or a less ambitious project, writers often experience exhilaration, fear, or dread. For Kristjana Gunnars, the call of a new project is “like someone you don’t know knocking on your door—you either choose to let the person in or not. It’s both exciting and dangerous to start a new manuscript.” This book is an engagement with that “stranger” called writing. Creative or imaginative writing is a complex process that involves more than intellect alone. Writers make use of everything: their sensibilities, history, culture, knowledge, experience, education, and even their biology. These essays seek out, and gather into a discussion, what writers have said about their own experiences in writing. Although the writers are from around the world and of very different backgrounds, the commonality of their remarks brings home the realization that writers everywhere are grappling with similar problems—with the seemingly simple problems of when, where, why, and what to write, but also larger questions such as the relationship between writer and society, or issues of privacy, appropriation, or homelessness. While none of these questions can be definitively answered, they can be fruitfully discussed. Originating as questions posed in creative-writing seminars, these essays have grown into companion texts for both writers and readers who want to participate in a conversation about what writers do.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAuthors. 0aAuthorship. 0aCreation (Literary, artistic, etc.). 0aCreative writing. 4aLanguage Arts & Disciplines: Creative Writing. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Writing / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920932940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889209329423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889209329/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles